\u00e9e, Mr Kapoor and Shobhana Kapoor's second daughter (2016\u20132018)\n* [[Nehalaxmi Iyer]] as Saumya Kapoor: Rudra's ex-wife, Mr Kapoor and Shobhana Kapoor's youngest daughter (2016\u201318)\n* [[Aryan Prajapati]] as Young Sahil Chaturvedi (2016\u201318)\n* Naman Mukul as Mr. Khanna: Oberoi's bodyguard (2016\u20132018)\n* [[Ayush Anand]] as Ranveer Singh Randhawa: Kamini's son, Priyanka's husband (2016\u201317)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abplive.in/television/things-to-get-intense-with-this-new-entry-in-ishqbaaz-429214|title=Things to get intense with this NEW ENTRY in ISHQBAAZ|date=10 October 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017|publisher=[[ABP News]]}}</ref>\n* [[Vrushika Mehta]] as Ishana<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Vrushika-Mehta-to-enter-Ishqbaaz/articleshow/53153836.cms|author=Tanvi Trivedi|title=Vrushika Mehta to enter 'Ishqbaaz'|agency=TNN|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=12 July 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Vrushika-Mehta-no-more-a-part-of-Ishqbaaz/articleshow/54561646.cms|title=Vrushika Mehta no more a part of Ishqbaaz|agency=TNN|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=28 September 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> (2016)\n* [[Krissann Barretto]] as Romi (2016\u201317)\n* Anisha Hinduja as Shobana Kapoor: wife of Mr Kapoor\n* Saurabh Kushwaha as Dushyant / Robin: Tia's husband\n* [[Surbhi Jyoti]] as Mallika Choudhary (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Cinema/2016-09-07/Surbhi-Jyoti-in-love-with-her-Ishqbaaaz-look-/252518|title=Surbhi Jyoti in love with her Ishqbaaaz look|date=7 September 2016|website=The Hans India}}</ref>\n* [[Shaleen Malhotra]] as Vikram Rana (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Shaleen-Malhotra-replaces-Karanvir-in-Ishqbaaz/articleshow/54266297.cms|title=Shaleen Malhotra replaces Karanvir in 'Ishqbaaz' - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n* [[Naved Aslam]] as Vikram Pradeep Rana (2016)\n* Karan Khanna as Daksh Khurana<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abplive.in/television/ishqbaaz-this-new-entrant-to-bring-huge-twist-in-anika-shivaays-life-440461|title=Ishqbaaz: This new entrant to bring a huge twist in Anika and Shivaay's life!|publisher=[[ABP News]]|date=4 November 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> (2016\u20132017, 2018)\n* [[Manasi Salvi]] as Ketaki Rana (2016)\n* [[Aashish Kaul]] as Mr. Chabra<ref name=entry>{{cite news|url=http://www.abplive.in/television/ishqbaaz-3-new-actors-set-to-enter-in-the-show-426600|title=ISHQBAAZ: 3 new actors set to enter in the show|publisher=[[ABP News]]|date=5 October 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> (2016)\n* Anandi Tripathi as Mrs. Chabra (2016)\n* Ish Thakkar as Dev Chabra<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indoamerican-news.com/?p=48003|title=Anika to again create 'troubles' for Shivaay in Ishqbaaaz|publisher=Indo American News|date=7 October 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> (2016)\n* Hiten Meghrajani as Reyaan Chabra:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indoamerican-news.com/anika-to-again-create-troubles-for-shivaay-in-ishqbaaaz/|title=Anika to again create \u2018troubles\u2019 for Shivaay in Ishqbaaaz - Indo American News|publisher=}}</ref> Saumya's ex-fianc\u00e9 (2016)\n* [[Sheeba Chaddha]] as Inspector Maadhuri (2016)\n* [[Amrapali Gupta]] as Kamini Khurana (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/telly-talk/gossip/article/i-was-bored-playing-negative-roles-ishqbaaaz-actress-amrapali-gupta/262246|title=I was bored playing negative roles: Ishqbaaaz actress Amrapali Gupta - Entertainment News|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>\n* [[Rahul Dev]] as Kaali Thakur (2017)\n* [[Anjali Mukhi]] as Nayantara (2017)\n* [[Additi Gupta]] as Ragini Malhotra (2017)\n* [[Ankit Raaj]] as Samarjeet Malhotra<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/ankit-raj-enters-ishqbaaaz-as-the-new-hero/articleshow/59054902.cms|author=Neha Maheshwri|title=Ankit Raj enters 'Ishqbaaaz' as the new hero|agency=TNN|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> (2017)\n* Danish Pandor as Vikram Thapar (2017)\n* Nitin Bhatia as Nandi \"Muthu Swami Iyer\" (2017)\n* Pratibha Tiwari as Tanya Abhay Singh Oberoi\n* Neelam Panchal as Sahil's Mother (2018)\n* [[Zain Imam]] as Mohit Malhotra (2018)\n* [[Mandana Karimi]] as Nancy Malhotra (2018)\n* [[Ishani Sharma]] as Pooja (2018)\n* Prakhar Toshniwal as Viraj (2018)\n* [[Kiran Janjani]] as Abhimanyu Raheja (2018)\n* [[Srishty Rode]] as Fiza Khan (2018)\n* [[Ankit Siwach]] as Farhan Khan (2018)\n* Veena Mehta as Kalyani's elder sister (2018\u20132019)\n* \n* Abhishek Tewari as Nikhil: Anika's ex-fianc\u00e9e (2018)\n* Manjiri Pupala as ACP Aditi Deshmukh (2018\u20132019)\n* Sharain Khanduja as Radhika Singh Oberoi: Gauri and Omkara's daughter (2018\u20132019)\n* Abhishek Singh Pathania as Dhruv Singh Oberoi: Bhavya and Rudra's son (2018\u20132019)\n* Pal John as Shivani Singh Oberoi: Annika and Shivaay's daughter; Shivaansh's sister (2018\u20132019)\n* Saransh Verma as Avi, Shivaansh's manager (2018\u20132019)\n* [[Supriya Pilgaonkar]] as Inspector Nandini Dixit (2018)\n*A nup Ingale as Junior Khanna: Shivaansh's bodyguard (2018\u20132019)\n* Manisha Singh Chauhan as Asiya: Shivaansh's publicist (2018\u20132019)\n* [[Amar Upadhyay]] as Adult Sahil Trivedi: Annika's younger brother (2019)\n\n===Guest stars===\n* [[Barun Sobti]] as Advay Singh Raizada - Shivaay's close friend, a special appearance to promote his show ''[[Iss Pyaar Ko Kya Naam Doon 3]]'' (2017)\n* [[Kriti Sanon]], [[Ayushmann Khurrana]] and [[Rajkummar Rao]] to promote their film ''[[Bareilly Ki Barfi]]'' (2017)\n* [[Badshah (rapper)|Badshah]] as himself, a special appearance for Shivaay-Anika's Haldi ceremony (2017)\n* Aakriti Sharma as Kullfi, a special appearance to promote her show ''[[Kullfi Kumarr Bajewala]]'' (2018)\n* [[Supriya Pathak]] as Hansa Parekh, to promote her new show ''[[Khichdi (2018 TV series)|Khichdi Returns]]'' (2018)\n* [[Antara Biswas]] as Daayan Mohana from [[Nazar (TV series)|''Nazar'']] (2018)\n\n==Production==\nInitially, the show focused on the three brothers and heirs of the Oberoi family; Shivaay, Omkara, and Rudra portrayed by [[Nakuul Mehta]], [[Kunal Jaisingh]] and [[Leenesh Mattoo]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/I-will-not-play-a-makkhis-boyfriend-in-a-serial-Nakuul-Mehta/articleshow/52944294.cms|title=I will not play a maakhi's boyfriend in a serial:Nakuul Mehta|author=Akash Wadhwa|date=28 June 2016|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=16 November 2017|agency=TNN}}</ref><ref name=\"Star Plus' 'Silsila Pyar Ka' and 'Dahleez' to be replaced by new shows\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/star-plus-silsila-pyar-ka-dahleez-be-replaced-by-new-shows-680933|author=Parismita Goswami|title=Star Plus' 'Silsila Pyar Ka' and 'Dahleez' to be replaced by new shows|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater, the show centered on the love story of Shivaay and Annika and Omkara's story with Gauri and Rudra's story with Bhavya was shifted to the spin-off series ''[[Dil Boley Oberoi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dil-bole-oberoi-is-ishqbaazs-spin-off-5-tv-characters-that-deserve-their-own-series-lifetv/1/882590.html|author=Anvita Singh|title=Dil Bole Oberoi is Ishqbaaz's spin-off; 5 TV characters that deserve their own series|newspaper=[[India Today]]|date=14 February 2017|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> Soon, the spin-off series was merged with this parent series.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 18 June 2018, a reboot version, ''Ishqbaaaz: Redux'', was launched with a new love story of the leads from the beginning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ishqbaaaz to present Shivaay and Anika\u2019s new love story |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/ishqbaaaz-to-present-shivaay-and-anika-new-love-story-5220345/ |accessdate=23 June 2018 |work=The Indian Express |date=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOwing to its declining viewership ratings, it took a leap in December 2018 which starred [[Nakuul Mehta]] and Manjiri Pupala.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/videos/television/video/actress-manjiri-pupala-to-romance-nakuul-mehta-in-ishqbaaz-post-leap-1398952-2018-11-29|title=Actress Manjiri Pupala to romance Nakuul Mehta in Ishqbaaz post leap|last=|first=|date=|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As it failed to increase the ratings, Pupala's character was turned negative, resulting in her resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/entertainment/television/ishqbaaaz-nakuul-mehtas-former-leading-lady-manjiri-pupala-aka-acp-aditi-confirms-quitting-the-show-926537|title=Manjiri Pupala aka ACP Aditi CONFIRMS quitting Nakuul Mehta's 'Ishqbaaaz'!|last=|first=|date=|website=Abp Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Eventually, [[Niti Taylor]] was roped to play Mannat Kaur Khurana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/soaps/story/kaisi-yeh-yaariaan-star-niti-taylor-to-make-tv-comeback-with-ishqbaaz-details-inside-1430401-2019-01-14|title=Kaisi Yeh Yaariaan star Niti Taylor to make TV comeback with Ishqbaaz. Details inside|last=|first=|date=|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The expected ratings were not delivered and it went off air on 15 March 2019.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Spin-off==\nA spin-off series, ''[[Dil Boley Oberoi]]'', premiered on 13 February 2017. It is acclaimed to be the first Indian soap to have a spin-off. On 7 July 2017, ''Dil Boley Oberoi'' ended and the storylines were merged back into ''Ishqbaaaz''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.mid-day.com/articles/indian-television-first-spin-off-show-dil-bole-oberoi-ishqbaaaz-television-news/18389162|title=Indian television's first spin-off show 'Dil Bole Oberoi' to go off air?}}</ref>\n\nIn Dil Boley Oberoi, [[Shrenu Parikh]] was introduced as Kunal Jaisingh's love interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bestmediainfo.com/2017/02/viewers-get-to-see-more-of-oberoi-family-with-star-plus-spin-off-stunt/|title=Viewers get to see more of Oberoi family with Star Plus\u2019 spin-off stunt}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Ishqbaaaz<br/>Original Sound Track\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Sanjeev Srivastava\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Album Artwork\n| released   = 07 August 2016\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Romance (music)|Romance]]<br>[[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 38:38\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[Star India]]<br>Screen Journal<br>[[SoundCloud]]\n| producer   = [[Gul Khan (producer)|Gul Khan]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Sanjeev Srivastava\n | type       = Album\n | prev_title = [[Revolver Rani#Soundtrack|Revolver Rani]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Ishqbaaaz (soundtrack)\n | year       = 2016\n | next_title = [[Kullfi Kumarr Bajewala#Soundtrack|Kullfi Kumarr Bajewala]]\n | next_year  = 2018\n}}\n}}\nThe ''Ishqbaaaz'' soundtrack was written by Shaheen Iqbal, and composed by Sanjeev Srivastava. Sanjeev Srivastava had composed the original songs and background score for the show. The original version of the album was released on 7 August 2016. \"O Jaana\", the theme song of the serial performed by [[Pamela Jain]] and Bhaven Dhanak.\n\"O Saathiya\", the theme song of [[Dil Boley Oberoi]], the album released on 1 May 2017. Firstly, the song was made for Omkara and Ishana, but after Ishana left, the song was not used at Ishqbaaaz. When Dil Boley Oberoi aired on, the female version by Pamela Jain was released, but now it also used on this show for Omkara and Gauri, after merging with Ishqbaaaz.\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column= Artist\n| headline    = Ishqbaaaz: Tracklisting\n| title1      = O Jaana\n| note1       = Female\n| extra1      = [[Pamela Jain]]\n| length1     = 04:24<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WjsGqRtQIFU|title=Ishqbaaz - O Jaana  NEW Song Female Version Full|first=|last=Screen Journal|publisher=|accessdate=2 February 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| title2      = O Jaana\n| note2       = Male\n| extra2      = Bhaven Dhanak\n| length2     = 04:25<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TcF8zMAP6p0|title=ISHQBAAZ - O JAANA NEW SONG MALE VERSION FULL|first=|last=Screen Journal|publisher=|accessdate=2 February 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| title3      = O Jaana\n| note3       = Duet\n| extra3      = Bhaven Dhanak & [[Pamela Jain]]\n| length3     = 04:23\n| title4      = O Jaana\n| note4       = Acoustic\n| extra4     = Bhaven Dhanak & [[Pamela Jain]]\n| length4     = 02:30\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column= Artist\n| headline        = Dil Boley Oberoi: Tracklisting\n| title1      =  O Saathiya\n| note1       = Female\n| extra1      = [[Pamela Jain]]\n| length1     = 06:55\n| title2      = O Saathiya\n| note2       = Male\n| extra2      = Bhaven Dhanak\n| length2     = 07:00<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ih2hJ8XWA9g|title=O Saathiya Jo Na Keh Sake Tum Ishqbaaz - Dil Bole Oberoi -  Ishkara Full Song - Kunal Jaisingh|first=|last=Screen Journal|publisher=|accessdate=2 February 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| title3      = O Saathiya\n| note3       = Duet\n| extra3      = Bhaven Dhanak & [[Pamela Jain]]\n| length3     = 06:58<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_e-Gty3ePF0|title=O Saathiya - Ishqbaaz Song - Rikara Romance - Omkara and Gauri - Shrenal - Screen Journal|first=|last=Screen Journal|publisher=|accessdate=2 February 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column= Artist\n| headline        = Special: Tracklisting\n| title1          = Lafzon Ka Ye Rishta Nahi\n| note1           = Family Song\n| extra1          = Various Artists\n| length1         = 02:00\n}}\n\n==Adaptations==\n\nIshqbaaaz was dubbed in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and released as ''Kadhala Kadhala''. It aired on [[Vijay Super]] and was discontinued even though more than 300 episodes were aired, and previously aired on [[Star Vijay]] as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotstar.com/in/tv/kadhala-kadhala/s-1108|title=Kadhala Kadhala on Hotstar|last=|first=|date=|website=Hotstar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The show has been officially remade in [[Kannada]] as ''Sathyam Shivam Sundaram'', airing on [[Star Suvarna]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/kannada/remake-soap-operas-rule-kannada-television/articleshow/69714322.cms|title=Remake soap operas rule Kannada television|last=|first=|date=|website=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is being directed by Sudharsan Srinivasan. Ishqbaaaz has been also dubbed into Arabic titled as ''Lil Ishq Junoon'' and it airs on [[MBC Bollywood]]. There is also a [[Malayalam]] dubbed version, ''Priyamanasam'' on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]] and a Telugu-dubbed version ''Prema Yuddam'' on [[Star Maa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotstar.com/in/tv/prema-yuddam/s-726|title=Prema Yuddam of Star Maa on Hotsar|last=|first=|date=|website=Hotstar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotstar.com/in/tv/priyamanasam/s-1181|title=Priyamanasam of Asianet on Hotstar|last=|first=|date=|website=Hotstar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Ishqbaaaz}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hotstar.com/tv/ishqbaaaz/9567 Ishqbaaaz] Streaming on [[Hotstar]]\n*{{IMDb title|5919914}}\n*{{TV Guide|946451}}\n{{Star Plus Shows}}\n{{4 Lions Films}}\n\n[[Category:2010s Indian television series]]\n[[Category:2016 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Indian drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Star Plus television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by 4 Lions Films]]\n", "name_user": "102.163.30.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ishqbaaaz"}
{"title_page": "Posse Comitatus Act", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|United States law limiting use of the federal military in domestic policy}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n{{About|the Posse Comitatus Act in the United States|other uses of ''posse comitatus''|Posse comitatus (disambiguation){{!}}Posse comitatus}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Posse Comitatus Act\n| longtitle= An act making appropriations for the support of the Army for the fiscal year ending June thirtieth, eighteen hundred and seventy-nine, and for other purposes.\n| othershorttitles = {{unbulleted list|Knott Amendment|Posse Comitatus Act of 1878}}\n| nickname= Army Appropriations Act of 1878\n| enacted by = 45th\n| effective date = June 18, 1878\n| public law url =http://legisworks.org/congress/45/session-2/chap-263.pdf\n| cite public law = 45-263\n| cite statutes at large = {{usstat|20|145}} ''aka'' 20 Stat. 152\n| acts amended =\n| title amended =\n| sections created = {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl =\n| introducedin    = House\n| introducedbill  = {{USBill|45|H.R.|4867}}\n| introducedby    = [[Herman L. Humphrey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Wisconsin|WI]]), [[William Kimmel]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Maryland|MD]])\n| introduceddate  = May 13, 1878\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = May 18, 1878\n| passedvote1 = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/h190 130\u2013117]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = June 6, 1878\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/s282 36\u201323]\n| conferencedate  = June 15, 1878\n| passedbody3     = House\n| passeddate3     = June 15, 1878\n| passedvote3     = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/h230 154\u201358]\n| passedbody4     = Senate\n| passeddate4     = June 15, 1878\n| passedvote4     = Agreed\n| signedpresident = [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]\n| signeddate      = June 18, 1878\n| amendments = 1956, 1981\n| SCOTUS cases =\n}}\nThe '''Posse Comitatus Act''' is a [[United States federal law]] ({{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}, original at {{USStat|20|152}}) signed on June 18, 1878, by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]. The purpose of the act \u2013 in concert with the [[Insurrection Act|Insurrection Act of 1807]] \u2013 is to limit the powers of the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] in using [[United States Armed Forces|federal military]] personnel to enforce [[Domestic policy|domestic policies]] within the [[United States]]. It was passed as an amendment to an army [[Appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation bill]] following the end of [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] and was updated in 1956 and 1981.\n\nThe act specifically applies only to the [[United States Army]] and, as amended in 1956, the [[United States Air Force]]. Although the act does not explicitly mention the [[United States Navy]] and the [[United States Marine Corps]], the [[United States Department of the Navy|Department of the Navy]] has prescribed regulations that are generally construed to give the act force with respect to those services as well. The act does not prevent the [[Army National Guard]] or the [[Air National Guard|Air]] [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] under [[U.S. state|state]] authority from acting in a [[law enforcement]] capacity within its home state or in an adjacent state if invited by that state's governor. The [[United States Coast Guard]] (under the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]]) and [[United States Space Force]] (under the [[United States Department of the Air Force|Department of the Air Force]]) are not covered by the Posse Comitatus Act either, primarily because although both are [[United States Armed Forces|armed service]]s, they also have [[Admiralty law|maritime]] and [[space law]] enforcement missions respectively.\n\nThe title of the act comes from the legal concept of ''[[posse comitatus]]'', the authority under which a county sheriff, or other law officer, conscripts any able-bodied person to assist in keeping the peace.\n\n==History==\nThe Act, \u00a7 15 of the appropriations bill for the Army for 1879, found at {{USStat|20|152}}, was a response to, and subsequent prohibition of, the [[military occupation]] of the former [[Confederate States of America|Confederate States]] by the [[United States Army]] during the twelve years of [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] (1865\u20131877) following the [[American Civil War]] (1861\u20131865). The president withdrew federal troops from the Southern States as a result of a compromise in one of the most disputed national elections in American history, the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 U.S. presidential election]]. [[Samuel J. Tilden]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate, defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of [[Ohio]] in the popular vote. Tilden garnered 184 [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral votes]] to Hayes' 165; 20 disputed electoral votes remained uncounted. After a bitter fight, Congress struck a deal resolving the dispute and awarded the presidency to Hayes. Known as the [[Compromise of 1877]], this agreement involved allowing South Carolina, Florida, and Louisiana to agree to certify Rutherford B. Hayes as the president in exchange for the removal of federal troops from the South, formally ending Reconstruction. <ref name=\"Military Law Review\">[https://www.jagcnet.army.mil/DOCLIBS/MILITARYLAWREVIEW.NSF/20a66345129fe3d885256e5b00571830/47c2b664085060fc85256e5b00576e6e/$FILE/Volume175Felicetti.pdf \"The Posse Comitatus Act]: Setting the record straight on 124 years of mischief and misunderstanding before any more damage is done,\" ''Military Law Review'', Vol. 175, 2003.</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]] places primary responsibility for the holding of [[election]]s in the hands of the individual states. The maintenance of peace, conduct of orderly elections, and prosecution of unlawful actions are all state responsibilities, pursuant of any state's role of exercising police power and maintaining law and order, whether part of a wider federation or a unitary state. During the local, state, and federal elections of 1874 and 1876 in the former Confederate States, all levels of government chose not to exercise their police powers to maintain law and order.<ref name=\"Military Law Review\" /> Some historians have concluded most Reconstruction governments did not have the power to suppress the violence.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nWhen the [[United States House of Representatives]] and [[United States Senate|United States Senators]] from the former Confederate States reached Washington, they set as a priority legislation to prohibit any future president or Congress from directing, by military order or federal legislation, the imposition of federal troops in any U.S. state.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} By the 1878 election, Congress was dominated by the Democratic Party which passed the Posse Comitatus Act in 1878.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} The Act did not end the conflict, as the 1879 Rider Wars led to the second longest shutdown of the US government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1851-1900/1879_rider_wars/|title=The 1879 Rider Wars &#124; US House of Representatives: History, Art & Archives|website=history.house.gov|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/money/2019/01/16/686079232/episode-888-the-first-shutdown|title=Episode 888: The First Shutdown|website=NPR.org|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref> According to historian Heather Cox Richardson, railroad executive [[Thomas A. Scott]] convinced President Hayes to use federal troops to end the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1877]], causing a backlash that motivated bipartisan support for the Posse Comitatus Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/radioboston/2018/04/06/april-6-2018-rb|title=Week In Review; espnW|website=www.wbur.org|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-20th century, the administration of President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] used an exception to the Posse Comitatus Act, derived from the [[Enforcement Acts]], to send federal troops into [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], during the [[Little Rock Nine|1957 school desegregation crisis]]. The Arkansas governor had opposed desegregation after the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in 1954 in the ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' that segregated public schools were unconstitutional. The Enforcement Acts, among other powers, allowed the president to call up military forces when state authorities were either unable or unwilling to suppress violence that were in opposition to the citizens' constitutional rights.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lieberman |first=Jethro |title=A Practical Companion to the Constitution: How the Supreme Court Has Ruled on Issues from Abortion to Zoning |publisher=University of California Press |year=1999 |isbn=0-520-21280-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/practicalcompani00lieb }}</ref>\n\nThe original Posse Comitatus Act referred mostly to the United States Army. The [[United States Air Force]], which had been incorporated within the Army until 1947, was added in 1956. The [[United States Navy]] and [[United States Marine Corps]] are not mentioned anywhere in the Act, but are subject to the same restrictions by [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] regulation.<ref name=\"nyt\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/25/us/25detain.html Mazzetti, Mark and Johnston, David. \"Bush Weighed Using Military in Arrests\"], ''New York Times,'' 22 June 2009</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] and [[United States Space Force]] are not included in the act even though they are part of the six armed services as both have explicitly given federal law enforcement authority on [[Admiralty law|maritime]] and [[space law]]s respectively.<ref name=\"EWAE\">{{cite document|title=THE CASE FOR SPACE: A Legislative Framework for an Independent United States Space Force|url=https://media.defense.gov/2020/Feb/12/2002248561/-1/-1/0/WF_73_GRANT_NEIL_THE_CASE_FOR_SPACE_A_LEGISLATIVE_FRAMEWORK_FOR_AN_INDEPENDENT_UNITED_STATES_SPACE_FORCE.PDF#page=22|authors=Dustin L. Grant and Matthew J. Neil|page=22\u201323|publisher=Wright Flyer Papers|date=February 2020}}</ref> The modern Coast Guard did not exist at the time the act became law in 1878. Its predecessor, the [[United States Revenue Cutter Service]], was primarily a customs enforcement agency and part of the [[United States Department of the Treasury]].<ref name=CGLEDET>http://www.uscg.mil/History/articles/LEDET_History.aspCoast Guard Law Enforcement Detachments (LEDETs): A History {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212070440/http://www.uscg.mil/History/articles/LEDET_History.asp |date=February 12, 2010 }}</ref> In 1915, when the Revenue Cutter Service and the [[United States Lifesaving Service]] were amalgamated to form the Coast Guard, the service was both explicitly made a military branch and explicitly given federal law enforcement authority.\n\n==Legislation==\nThe original provision was enacted as Section 15 of chapter 263, of the Acts of the 2nd session of the [[45th United States Congress|45th Congress]].\n{{quote|{{sm|Sec.}} 15. From and after the passage of this act it shall not be lawful to employ any part of the Army of the United States, as a posse comitatus, or otherwise, for the purpose of executing the laws, except in such cases and under such circumstances as such employment of said force may be expressly authorized by the Constitution or by act of Congress; and no money appropriated by this act shall be used to pay any of the expenses incurred in the employment of any troops in violation of this section and any person willfully violating the provisions of this section shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction thereof shall be punished by fine not exceeding ten thousand dollars or imprisonment not exceeding two years or by both such fine and imprisonment<ref>[[s:Page:United States Statutes at Large Volume 20.djvu/177|Text at Wikisource]]</ref>}}\n\nThe text of the relevant legislation is as follows:\n: {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}. Use of Army and Air Force as posse comitatus\n:: Whoever, except in cases and under circumstances expressly authorized by the Constitution or Act of Congress, willfully uses any part of the Army or the Air Force as a posse comitatus or otherwise to execute the laws shall be fined under this title or imprisoned not more than two years, or both.\n\nAlso notable is the following provision within [[Title 10 of the United States Code]] (which concerns generally the organization and regulation of the armed forces and Department of Defense):\n\n:{{UnitedStatesCode|10|275}}. Restriction on direct participation by military personnel\n::The [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] shall prescribe such regulations as may be necessary to ensure that any activity (including the provision of any equipment or facility or the assignment or detail of any personnel) under this chapter does not include or permit direct participation by a member of the Army, Navy, Air Force, or Marine Corps in a search, seizure, arrest, or other similar activity unless participation in such activity by such member is otherwise authorized by law.\n\n===2006\u201307 suspension===\nIn 2006, Congress modified the Insurrection Act as part of the [[H.R. 5122 (2006)|2007 Defense Authorization Bill]] ([[Insurrection Act#Repeal of amendments|repealed]] as of 2008). On September 26, 2006, President [[George W. Bush]] urged Congress to consider revising federal laws so that U.S. armed forces could restore public order and enforce laws in the aftermath of a natural disaster, terrorist attack or incident, or other condition. [[Insurrection Act#Amendments of 2006|These changes]] were included in the [[John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007]] ({{USBill|109|HR|5122}}), which was signed into law on October 17, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/109/hr5122|title=John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007 (2006 - H.R. 5122)|website=GovTrack.us|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSection 1076 is titled \"Use of the Armed Forces in major public emergencies.\" It provided that:\n{{quote|The President may employ the armed forces ... to ... restore public order and enforce the laws of the United States when, as a result of a natural disaster, epidemic, or other serious public health emergency, terrorist attack or incident, or other condition ... the President determines that ... domestic violence has occurred to such an extent that the constituted authorities of the State or possession are incapable of maintaining public order ... or [to] suppress, in a State, any insurrection, domestic violence, unlawful combination, or conspiracy if such ... a condition ... so hinders the execution of the laws ... that any part or class of its people is deprived of a right, privilege, immunity, or protection named in the Constitution and secured by law ... or opposes or obstructs the execution of the laws of the United States or impedes the course of justice under those laws.''<ref>{{USBill|109|HR|5122}}, pp. 322\u201323</ref>}}\n\nIn 2008, these changes in the [[Insurrection Act]] of 1807 were [[Insurrection Act#Repeal of amendments|repealed in their entirety]], reverting to the previous wording of the Insurrection Act.<ref>{{cite news | title = H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008 | work = GovTrack.us | year = 2008 | url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h110-4986 | accessdate = January 24, 2008}}</ref> It was originally written to limit presidential power as much as possible in the event of insurrection, rebellion, or lawlessness.\n\n=== 2011 modification ===\nIn 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] signed [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] into law. Section 1021(b)(2) extended the definition of a \"covered person\", ''i.e.'', someone possibly subject to detention under this law,{{dubious|date=November 2018}}<!-- the law as quoted above doesn't mention anything about detentions?--> to include:\n<blockquote> A person who was a part of or substantially supported [[al-Qaeda]], the [[Taliban]], or associated forces that are engaged in hostilities against the United States or its coalition partners, including any person who has committed a belligerent act or has directly supported such hostilities in aid of such enemy forces.<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-112publ81/pdf/PLAW-112publ81.pdf GPO text of Public Law 112-81] (PDF)</ref></blockquote>Section 1021(e) purports to limit the scope of said authority with the text, \"Nothing in this section shall be construed to affect existing law or authorities relating to the detention of United States citizens, lawful resident aliens of the United States, or any other persons who are captured or arrested in the United States.\"<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-112publ81/pdf/PLAW-112publ81.pdf \"Text of Public Law 112-81\"] (PDF), GPO</ref>\n\n==Exclusions and limitations==\nThere are a number of situations in which the Act does not apply. These include:\n* [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] units, [[state defense force]]s, and [[naval militia]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cna.org/CNA_files/PDF/D0015586.A1.pdf#page=32 |title=The Naval Militia: A Neglected Asset? |last=Nofi |first=Albert A. |date=July 2007 |website= |publisher=[[CNA (nonprofit)|CNA]] |access-date=19 February 2019 |quote=}}</ref> while under the authority of the [[Governor (United States)|governor of a state]]. However, only the National Guard can be federalized under {{UnitedStatesCode|10|12406}}, which shifts control from the state governor to the President, making them subject to the PCA as well.\n* Federal troops used in accordance to the [[Insurrection Act]], as was the case with the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] and [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]] being sent to curtail the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]].\n* Under {{UnitedStatesCode|18|831}}, the [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] may request that the [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] provide emergency assistance if domestic law enforcement is inadequate to address certain types of threats involving the release of [[Special nuclear material|nuclear materials]], such as potential use of a [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear]] or [[radiological weapon]]. Such assistance may be by any personnel under the authority of the Department of Defense, provided such assistance does not adversely affect U.S. military preparedness. The only exemption is the deployment of nuclear materials on the part of the United States Armed Forces.\n* Support roles under the [[Joint Special Operations Command]].\n* Provide surveillance, intelligence gathering, observation, and equipment for domestic law enforcement on operations such as drug interdiction and counter-terrorism missions.\n\n===Exclusion applicable to U.S. Coast Guard and U.S. Space Farce===\n:''See also the [[Missions of the United States Coast Guard]] for more information on U.S. Coast Guard law enforcement activities.''\n\nAlthough it is an armed service,<ref name=\"About the United States Coast Guard\">{{Cite web|url=https://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091015130425/http://www.uscg.mil/top/about/|title=USCG: About Us|website=arquivo.pt|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref> the U.S. Coast Guard, which operates under the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] during peacetime, is not restricted by the Posse Comitatus Act but has explicit authority to enforce federal law. This is true even when the Coast Guard is operating as a service within the [[United States Navy]] during wartime.<ref name=\"CGLEDET\" />\n\nIn December 1981, the [[Military Cooperation with Civilian Law Enforcement Agencies Act]] was enacted clarifying permissible military assistance to domestic law enforcement agencies and the Coast Guard, especially in combating [[drug smuggling]] into the United States. Posse Comitatus clarifications emphasize supportive and technical assistance (''e.g.'', use of facilities, vessels, and aircraft, as well as intelligence support, technological aid, and surveillance) while generally prohibiting direct participation of U.S. military personnel in law enforcement (''e.g.'', search, seizure, and arrests). For example, a U.S. Navy vessel may be used to track, follow, and stop a vessel suspected of drug smuggling, but Coast Guard [[Law Enforcement Detachments]] (LEDETs) embarked aboard the Navy vessel would perform the actual boarding and, if needed, arrest the suspect vessel's crew.<ref name=\"CGLEDET\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2019, the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]] authorized the creation of the [[United States Space Force]], the sixth U.S. military branch under the [[United States Department of the Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Signs Law Establishing U.S. Space Force|url=https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/2046035/trump-signs-law-establishing-us-space-force/|author=Jim Garamone|publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]]|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, Air Force Major Generals Dustin L. Grant and Matthew J. Neil said in their paper ''The Case for Space: A Legislative Framework for an Independent United States Space Force'' that the Space Force was established independently to make enforcing U.S. [[space law]]s permissible, as such activity would be strictly prohibited under the Air Force branch regarding the Posse Comitatus Act.<ref name=\"EWAE\"></ref>\n\n===Advisory and support roles===\nFederal troops have a long history of domestic roles, including occupying secessionist Southern states during Reconstruction and putting down major urban riots. The Posse Comitatus Act prohibits the use of active duty personnel to \"execute the laws\"; however, there is disagreement over whether this language may apply to troops used in an advisory, support, disaster response, or other homeland defense role, as opposed to domestic law enforcement.<ref name=\"Military Law Review\" />\n\nOn March 10, 2009, members of the [[Military Police Corps (United States)|U.S. Army Military Police Corps]] from [[Fort Rucker]] were deployed to [[Samson, Alabama]], in response to [[Geneva County massacre|a murder spree]]. Samson officials confirmed that the soldiers assisted in traffic control and securing the crime scene. The [[governor of Alabama]] did not request military assistance nor did President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] authorize their deployment. Subsequent investigation found that the Posse Comitatus Act was violated and several military members received \"administrative actions\".<ref>[http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2009/10/army_reviews_shows_troop_use_i.html Army reviews shows troop use in Samson killing spree violated federal law], ''Birmingham News''</ref><ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA520027&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf Revolutionizing Northern Command], Lt. Col. Gary L. McGinniss, U.S. Army</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Great Railroad Strike of 1877]]\n* [[List of military actions by or within the United States]]\n* [[Martial law]]\n* [[Militarization of police]]\n* [[Separation of military and police roles]]\n* [[National Security and Homeland Security Presidential Directive]]\n* [[Operation Garden Plot]]\n* [[Union violence in the United States]]\n* [[United States Northern Command]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Hendell, Garri B. [http://publius.oxfordjournals.org/content/41/2/336 \"Domestic Use of the Armed Forces to Maintain Law and Order: ''posse comitatus'' Pitfalls at the Inauguration of the 44th President\"], ''Publius'' (2011) 41(2): 336\u201348 {{doi|10.1093/publius/pjq014}}\n* Lindorff, David. \"Could It Happen Here?\". ''Mother Jones'' magazine, April 1988.\n* ''The Posse Comitatus Act of 1878: A Documentary History.'' Buffalo, NY: W.S. Hein, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-8377-3900-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}} Use of Army and Air Force as Posse Comitatus\n* [http://openscholarship.wustl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1576&context=law_lawreview The Posse Comitatus Act: A Principle in Need of Renewal], Washington University Law Quarterly Vol 75 No. 2\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/natsec/R42659.pdf The Posse Comitatus Act and Related Matters: The Use of the Military to Execute Civilian Law] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA565078 Should the Posse Comitatus Act be Changed to Effectively Support Local Law Enforcement?] [[United States Army War College|U.S. Army War College]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h109-5122 John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007]\n* [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-112s1867es/pdf/BILLS-112s1867es.pdf] Bill Text 112th Congress (2011\u20132012) S.1867.ES\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/18/pg18.html] Federalist Paper #29 ''Concerning the Militia'', Alexander Hamilton, pub. 10 January 1788\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1878 in law]]\n[[Category:United States federal criminal legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal defense and national security legislation]]\n[[Category:United States military policies]]\n[[Category:1878 in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|United States law limiting use of the federal military in domestic policy}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n{{About|the Posse Comitatus Act in the United States|other uses of ''posse comitatus''|Posse comitatus (disambiguation){{!}}Posse comitatus}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Posse Comitatus Act\n| longtitle= An act making appropriations for the support of the Army for the fiscal year ending June thirtieth, eighteen hundred and seventy-nine, and for other purposes.\n| othershorttitles = {{unbulleted list|Knott Amendment|Posse Comitatus Act of 1878}}\n| nickname= Army Appropriations Act of 1878\n| enacted by = 45th\n| effective date = June 18, 1878\n| public law url =http://legisworks.org/congress/45/session-2/chap-263.pdf\n| cite public law = 45-263\n| cite statutes at large = {{usstat|20|145}} ''aka'' 20 Stat. 152\n| acts amended =\n| title amended =\n| sections created = {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl =\n| introducedin    = House\n| introducedbill  = {{USBill|45|H.R.|4867}}\n| introducedby    = [[Herman L. Humphrey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Wisconsin|WI]]), [[William Kimmel]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Maryland|MD]])\n| introduceddate  = May 13, 1878\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = May 18, 1878\n| passedvote1 = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/h190 130\u2013117]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = June 6, 1878\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/s282 36\u201323]\n| conferencedate  = June 15, 1878\n| passedbody3     = House\n| passeddate3     = June 15, 1878\n| passedvote3     = [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/45-2/h230 154\u201358]\n| passedbody4     = Senate\n| passeddate4     = June 15, 1878\n| passedvote4     = Agreed\n| signedpresident = [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]\n| signeddate      = June 18, 1878\n| amendments = 1956, 1981\n| SCOTUS cases =\n}}\nThe '''Posse Comitatus Act''' is a [[United States federal law]] ({{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}, original at {{USStat|20|152}}) signed on June 18, 1878, by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]. The purpose of the act \u2013 in concert with the [[Insurrection Act|Insurrection Act of 1807]] \u2013 is to limit the powers of the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] in using [[United States Armed Forces|federal military]] personnel to enforce [[Domestic policy|domestic policies]] within the [[United States]]. It was passed as an amendment to an army [[Appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation bill]] following the end of [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] and was updated in 1956 and 1981.\n\nThe act specifically applies only to the [[United States Army]] and, as amended in 1956, the [[United States Air Force]]. Although the act does not explicitly mention the [[United States Navy]] and the [[United States Marine Corps]], the [[United States Department of the Navy|Department of the Navy]] has prescribed regulations that are generally construed to give the act force with respect to those services as well. The act does not prevent the [[Army National Guard]] or the [[Air National Guard|Air]] [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] under [[U.S. state|state]] authority from acting in a [[law enforcement]] capacity within its home state or in an adjacent state if invited by that state's governor. The [[United States Coast Guard]] (under the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]]) and [[United States Space Force]] (under the [[United States Department of the Air Force|Department of the Air Force]]) are not covered by the Posse Comitatus Act either, primarily because although both are [[United States Armed Forces|armed service]]s, they also have [[Admiralty law|maritime]] and [[space law]] enforcement missions respectively.\n\nThe title of the act comes from the legal concept of ''[[posse comitatus]]'', the authority under which a county sheriff, or other law officer, conscripts any able-bodied person to assist in keeping the peace.\n\n==History==\nThe Act, \u00a7 15 of the appropriations bill for the Army for 1879, found at {{USStat|20|152}}, was a response to, and subsequent prohibition of, the [[military occupation]] of the former [[Confederate States of America|Confederate States]] by the [[United States Army]] during the twelve years of [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] (1865\u20131877) following the [[American Civil War]] (1861\u20131865). The president withdrew federal troops from the Southern States as a result of a compromise in one of the most disputed national elections in American history, the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 U.S. presidential election]]. [[Samuel J. Tilden]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate, defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of [[Ohio]] in the popular vote. Tilden garnered 184 [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral votes]] to Hayes' 165; 20 disputed electoral votes remained uncounted. After a bitter fight, Congress struck a deal resolving the dispute and awarded the presidency to Hayes. Known as the [[Compromise of 1877]], this agreement involved allowing South Carolina, Florida, and Louisiana to agree to certify Rutherford B. Hayes as the president in exchange for the removal of federal troops from the South, formally ending Reconstruction. <ref name=\"Military Law Review\">[https://www.jagcnet.army.mil/DOCLIBS/MILITARYLAWREVIEW.NSF/20a66345129fe3d885256e5b00571830/47c2b664085060fc85256e5b00576e6e/$FILE/Volume175Felicetti.pdf \"The Posse Comitatus Act]: Setting the record straight on 124 years of mischief and misunderstanding before any more damage is done,\" ''Military Law Review'', Vol. 175, 2003.</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]] places primary responsibility for the holding of [[election]]s in the hands of the individual states. The maintenance of peace, conduct of orderly elections, and prosecution of unlawful actions are all state responsibilities, pursuant of any state's role of exercising police power and maintaining law and order, whether part of a wider federation or a unitary state. During the local, state, and federal elections of 1874 and 1876 in the former Confederate States, all levels of government chose not to exercise their police powers to maintain law and order.<ref name=\"Military Law Review\" /> Some historians have concluded most Reconstruction governments did not have the power to suppress the violence.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nWhen the [[United States House of Representatives]] and [[United States Senate|United States Senators]] from the former Confederate States reached Washington, they set as a priority legislation to prohibit any future president or Congress from directing, by military order or federal legislation, the imposition of federal troops in any U.S. state.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} By the 1878 election, Congress was dominated by the Democratic Party which passed the Posse Comitatus Act in 1878.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} The Act did not end the conflict, as the 1879 Rider Wars led to the second longest shutdown of the US government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1851-1900/1879_rider_wars/|title=The 1879 Rider Wars &#124; US House of Representatives: History, Art & Archives|website=history.house.gov|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/money/2019/01/16/686079232/episode-888-the-first-shutdown|title=Episode 888: The First Shutdown|website=NPR.org|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref> According to historian Heather Cox Richardson, railroad executive [[Thomas A. Scott]] convinced President Hayes to use federal troops to end the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1877]], causing a backlash that motivated bipartisan support for the Posse Comitatus Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/radioboston/2018/04/06/april-6-2018-rb|title=Week In Review; espnW|website=www.wbur.org|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-20th century, the administration of President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] used an exception to the Posse Comitatus Act, derived from the [[Enforcement Acts]], to send federal troops into [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], during the [[Little Rock Nine|1957 school desegregation crisis]]. The Arkansas governor had opposed desegregation after the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in 1954 in the ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' that segregated public schools were unconstitutional. The Enforcement Acts, among other powers, allowed the president to call up military forces when state authorities were either unable or unwilling to suppress violence that were in opposition to the citizens' constitutional rights.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lieberman |first=Jethro |title=A Practical Companion to the Constitution: How the Supreme Court Has Ruled on Issues from Abortion to Zoning |publisher=University of California Press |year=1999 |isbn=0-520-21280-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/practicalcompani00lieb }}</ref>\n\nThe original Posse Comitatus Act referred mostly to the United States Army. The [[United States Air Force]], which had been incorporated within the Army until 1947, was added in 1956. The [[United States Navy]] and [[United States Marine Corps]] are not mentioned anywhere in the Act, but are subject to the same restrictions by [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] regulation.<ref name=\"nyt\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/25/us/25detain.html Mazzetti, Mark and Johnston, David. \"Bush Weighed Using Military in Arrests\"], ''New York Times,'' 22 June 2009</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] and [[United States Space Force]] are not included in the act even though they are part of the six armed services as both have explicitly given federal law enforcement authority on [[Admiralty law|maritime]] and [[space law]]s respectively.<ref name=\"EWAE\">{{cite document|title=THE CASE FOR SPACE: A Legislative Framework for an Independent United States Space Force|url=https://media.defense.gov/2020/Feb/12/2002248561/-1/-1/0/WF_73_GRANT_NEIL_THE_CASE_FOR_SPACE_A_LEGISLATIVE_FRAMEWORK_FOR_AN_INDEPENDENT_UNITED_STATES_SPACE_FORCE.PDF#page=22|authors=Dustin L. Grant and Matthew J. Neil|page=22\u201323|publisher=Wright Flyer Papers|date=February 2020}}</ref> The modern Coast Guard did not exist at the time the act became law in 1878. Its predecessor, the [[United States Revenue Cutter Service]], was primarily a customs enforcement agency and part of the [[United States Department of the Treasury]].<ref name=CGLEDET>http://www.uscg.mil/History/articles/LEDET_History.aspCoast Guard Law Enforcement Detachments (LEDETs): A History {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212070440/http://www.uscg.mil/History/articles/LEDET_History.asp |date=February 12, 2010 }}</ref> In 1915, when the Revenue Cutter Service and the [[United States Lifesaving Service]] were amalgamated to form the Coast Guard, the service was both explicitly made a military branch and explicitly given federal law enforcement authority.\n\n==Legislation==\nThe original provision was enacted as Section 15 of chapter 263, of the Acts of the 2nd session of the [[45th United States Congress|45th Congress]].\n{{quote|{{sm|Sec.}} 15. From and after the passage of this act it shall not be lawful to employ any part of the Army of the United States, as a posse comitatus, or otherwise, for the purpose of executing the laws, except in such cases and under such circumstances as such employment of said force may be expressly authorized by the Constitution or by act of Congress; and no money appropriated by this act shall be used to pay any of the expenses incurred in the employment of any troops in violation of this section and any person willfully violating the provisions of this section shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction thereof shall be punished by fine not exceeding ten thousand dollars or imprisonment not exceeding two years or by both such fine and imprisonment<ref>[[s:Page:United States Statutes at Large Volume 20.djvu/177|Text at Wikisource]]</ref>}}\n\nThe text of the relevant legislation is as follows:\n: {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}}. Use of Army and Air Force as posse comitatus\n:: Whoever, except in cases and under circumstances expressly authorized by the Constitution or Act of Congress, willfully uses any part of the Army or the Air Force as a posse comitatus or otherwise to execute the laws shall be fined under this title or imprisoned not more than two years, or both.\n\nAlso notable is the following provision within [[Title 10 of the United States Code]] (which concerns generally the organization and regulation of the armed forces and Department of Defense):\n\n:{{UnitedStatesCode|10|275}}. Restriction on direct participation by military personnel\n::The [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] shall prescribe such regulations as may be necessary to ensure that any activity (including the provision of any equipment or facility or the assignment or detail of any personnel) under this chapter does not include or permit direct participation by a member of the Army, Navy, Air Force, or Marine Corps in a search, seizure, arrest, or other similar activity unless participation in such activity by such member is otherwise authorized by law.\n\n===2006\u201307 suspension===\nIn 2006, Congress modified the Insurrection Act as part of the [[H.R. 5122 (2006)|2007 Defense Authorization Bill]] ([[Insurrection Act#Repeal of amendments|repealed]] as of 2008). On September 26, 2006, President [[George W. Bush]] urged Congress to consider revising federal laws so that U.S. armed forces could restore public order and enforce laws in the aftermath of a natural disaster, terrorist attack or incident, or other condition. [[Insurrection Act#Amendments of 2006|These changes]] were included in the [[John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007]] ({{USBill|109|HR|5122}}), which was signed into law on October 17, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/109/hr5122|title=John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007 (2006 - H.R. 5122)|website=GovTrack.us|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSection 1076 is titled \"Use of the Armed Forces in major public emergencies.\" It provided that:\n{{quote|The President may employ the armed forces ... to ... restore public order and enforce the laws of the United States when, as a result of a natural disaster, epidemic, or other serious public health emergency, terrorist attack or incident, or other condition ... the President determines that ... domestic violence has occurred to such an extent that the constituted authorities of the State or possession are incapable of maintaining public order ... or [to] suppress, in a State, any insurrection, domestic violence, unlawful combination, or conspiracy if such ... a condition ... so hinders the execution of the laws ... that any part or class of its people is deprived of a right, privilege, immunity, or protection named in the Constitution and secured by law ... or opposes or obstructs the execution of the laws of the United States or impedes the course of justice under those laws.''<ref>{{USBill|109|HR|5122}}, pp. 322\u201323</ref>}}\n\nIn 2008, these changes in the [[Insurrection Act]] of 1807 were [[Insurrection Act#Repeal of amendments|repealed in their entirety]], reverting to the previous wording of the Insurrection Act.<ref>{{cite news | title = H.R. 4986: National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2008 | work = GovTrack.us | year = 2008 | url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h110-4986 | accessdate = January 24, 2008}}</ref> It was originally written to limit presidential power as much as possible in the event of insurrection, rebellion, or lawlessness.\n\n=== 2011 modification ===\nIn 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] signed [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] into law. Section 1021(b)(2) extended the definition of a \"covered person\", ''i.e.'', someone possibly subject to detention under this law,{{dubious|date=November 2018}}<!-- the law as quoted above doesn't mention anything about detentions?--> to include:\n<blockquote> A person who was a part of or substantially supported [[al-Qaeda]], the [[Taliban]], or associated forces that are engaged in hostilities against the United States or its coalition partners, including any person who has committed a belligerent act or has directly supported such hostilities in aid of such enemy forces.<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-112publ81/pdf/PLAW-112publ81.pdf GPO text of Public Law 112-81] (PDF)</ref></blockquote>Section 1021(e) purports to limit the scope of said authority with the text, \"Nothing in this section shall be construed to affect existing law or authorities relating to the detention of United States citizens, lawful resident aliens of the United States, or any other persons who are captured or arrested in the United States.\"<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-112publ81/pdf/PLAW-112publ81.pdf \"Text of Public Law 112-81\"] (PDF), GPO</ref>\n\n==Exclusions and limitations==\nThere are a number of situations in which the Act does not apply. These include:\n* [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] units, [[state defense force]]s, and [[naval militia]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cna.org/CNA_files/PDF/D0015586.A1.pdf#page=32 |title=The Naval Militia: A Neglected Asset? |last=Nofi |first=Albert A. |date=July 2007 |website= |publisher=[[CNA (nonprofit)|CNA]] |access-date=19 February 2019 |quote=}}</ref> while under the authority of the [[Governor (United States)|governor of a state]]. However, only the National Guard can be federalized under {{UnitedStatesCode|10|12406}}, which shifts control from the state governor to the President, making them subject to the PCA as well.\n* Federal troops used in accordance to the [[Insurrection Act]], as was the case with the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] and [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]] being sent to curtail the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]].\n* Under {{UnitedStatesCode|18|831}}, the [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] may request that the [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] provide emergency assistance if domestic law enforcement is inadequate to address certain types of threats involving the release of [[Special nuclear material|nuclear materials]], such as potential use of a [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear]] or [[radiological weapon]]. Such assistance may be by any personnel under the authority of the Department of Defense, provided such assistance does not adversely affect U.S. military preparedness. The only exemption is the deployment of nuclear materials on the part of the United States Armed Forces.\n* Support roles under the [[Joint Special Operations Command]].\n* Provide surveillance, intelligence gathering, observation, and equipment for domestic law enforcement on operations such as drug interdiction and counter-terrorism missions.\n\n===Exclusion applicable to U.S. Coast Guard and U.S. Space Force===\n:''See also the [[Missions of the United States Coast Guard]] for more information on U.S. Coast Guard law enforcement activities.''\n\nAlthough it is an armed service,<ref name=\"About the United States Coast Guard\">{{Cite web|url=https://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091015130425/http://www.uscg.mil/top/about/|title=USCG: About Us|website=arquivo.pt|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref> the U.S. Coast Guard, which operates under the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] during peacetime, is not restricted by the Posse Comitatus Act but has explicit authority to enforce federal law. This is true even when the Coast Guard is operating as a service within the [[United States Navy]] during wartime.<ref name=\"CGLEDET\" />\n\nIn December 1981, the [[Military Cooperation with Civilian Law Enforcement Agencies Act]] was enacted clarifying permissible military assistance to domestic law enforcement agencies and the Coast Guard, especially in combating [[drug smuggling]] into the United States. Posse Comitatus clarifications emphasize supportive and technical assistance (''e.g.'', use of facilities, vessels, and aircraft, as well as intelligence support, technological aid, and surveillance) while generally prohibiting direct participation of U.S. military personnel in law enforcement (''e.g.'', search, seizure, and arrests). For example, a U.S. Navy vessel may be used to track, follow, and stop a vessel suspected of drug smuggling, but Coast Guard [[Law Enforcement Detachments]] (LEDETs) embarked aboard the Navy vessel would perform the actual boarding and, if needed, arrest the suspect vessel's crew.<ref name=\"CGLEDET\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2019, the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]] authorized the creation of the [[United States Space Force]], the sixth U.S. military branch under the [[United States Department of the Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Signs Law Establishing U.S. Space Force|url=https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/2046035/trump-signs-law-establishing-us-space-force/|author=Jim Garamone|publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]]|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, Air Force Major Generals Dustin L. Grant and Matthew J. Neil said in their paper ''The Case for Space: A Legislative Framework for an Independent United States Space Force'' that the Space Force was established independently to make enforcing U.S. [[space law]]s permissible, as such activity would be strictly prohibited under the Air Force branch regarding the Posse Comitatus Act.<ref name=\"EWAE\"></ref>\n\n===Advisory and support roles===\nFederal troops have a long history of domestic roles, including occupying secessionist Southern states during Reconstruction and putting down major urban riots. The Posse Comitatus Act prohibits the use of active duty personnel to \"execute the laws\"; however, there is disagreement over whether this language may apply to troops used in an advisory, support, disaster response, or other homeland defense role, as opposed to domestic law enforcement.<ref name=\"Military Law Review\" />\n\nOn March 10, 2009, members of the [[Military Police Corps (United States)|U.S. Army Military Police Corps]] from [[Fort Rucker]] were deployed to [[Samson, Alabama]], in response to [[Geneva County massacre|a murder spree]]. Samson officials confirmed that the soldiers assisted in traffic control and securing the crime scene. The [[governor of Alabama]] did not request military assistance nor did President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] authorize their deployment. Subsequent investigation found that the Posse Comitatus Act was violated and several military members received \"administrative actions\".<ref>[http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2009/10/army_reviews_shows_troop_use_i.html Army reviews shows troop use in Samson killing spree violated federal law], ''Birmingham News''</ref><ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA520027&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf Revolutionizing Northern Command], Lt. Col. Gary L. McGinniss, U.S. Army</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Great Railroad Strike of 1877]]\n* [[List of military actions by or within the United States]]\n* [[Martial law]]\n* [[Militarization of police]]\n* [[Separation of military and police roles]]\n* [[National Security and Homeland Security Presidential Directive]]\n* [[Operation Garden Plot]]\n* [[Union violence in the United States]]\n* [[United States Northern Command]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Hendell, Garri B. [http://publius.oxfordjournals.org/content/41/2/336 \"Domestic Use of the Armed Forces to Maintain Law and Order: ''posse comitatus'' Pitfalls at the Inauguration of the 44th President\"], ''Publius'' (2011) 41(2): 336\u201348 {{doi|10.1093/publius/pjq014}}\n* Lindorff, David. \"Could It Happen Here?\". ''Mother Jones'' magazine, April 1988.\n* ''The Posse Comitatus Act of 1878: A Documentary History.'' Buffalo, NY: W.S. Hein, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-8377-3900-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{UnitedStatesCode|18|1385}} Use of Army and Air Force as Posse Comitatus\n* [http://openscholarship.wustl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1576&context=law_lawreview The Posse Comitatus Act: A Principle in Need of Renewal], Washington University Law Quarterly Vol 75 No. 2\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/natsec/R42659.pdf The Posse Comitatus Act and Related Matters: The Use of the Military to Execute Civilian Law] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA565078 Should the Posse Comitatus Act be Changed to Effectively Support Local Law Enforcement?] [[United States Army War College|U.S. Army War College]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h109-5122 John Warner National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2007]\n* [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-112s1867es/pdf/BILLS-112s1867es.pdf] Bill Text 112th Congress (2011\u20132012) S.1867.ES\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/18/pg18.html] Federalist Paper #29 ''Concerning the Militia'', Alexander Hamilton, pub. 10 January 1788\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1878 in law]]\n[[Category:United States federal criminal legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal defense and national security legislation]]\n[[Category:United States military policies]]\n[[Category:1878 in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2601:348:4180:8360:8