= \n | yGrid =\n}}\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March 2020 ===\n[[File:KK highway deserted at night throughout the MCO.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Kota Kinabalu]] highway deserted at night throughout the [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] (MCO) in March.]]\nOn 12 March 2020, Sabah reported its first positive case involving a male resident from [[Tawau District]] who is one of the participant in the Muslim religious gathering at [[Sri Petaling]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]]. He began to developed symptoms after returning and was subsequently transferred to Tawau Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|title=Sabah's first Covid-19 case found in Tawau|work=New Straits Times|via=Daily Express|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318052110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A second positive case was reported the following day in Benoni's [[Papar District]] which is also originated from the religious gathering where he was then transferred to [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Kota Kinabalu|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]] for further treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148674/exclusive-sabah-s-second-positive-covid-19-case-in-papar/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Sabah's second positive Covid-19 case in Papar|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318052110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 14 new confirmed cases were recorded within the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148680/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-15/|title=14 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 15|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318054827/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148680/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-15/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 March, the Sabah State Health Department reported that another 11 new cases were confirmed in the state which bringing the total to 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148755/11-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-26/|title=11 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 26|work=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318055027/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148755/11-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-26/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further spike to 82 positive cases has been reported which making Sabah the third most affected by the virus after [[Selangor]] and Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148946/25-new-cases-in-sabah-make-it-82/|title=25 new cases in Sabah make it 82|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318054427/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148946/25-new-cases-in-sabah-make-it-82/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Earlier since the first positive case was reported, the State Health Department has warned there will be more positive cases to be detected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/expect-more-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-says-state-health-director|title=Expect more Covid-19 cases in Sabah, says state Health Director|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319064439/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/expect-more-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-says-state-health-director|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148679/possibly-more-sabah-covid-19-cases-but-stay-calm-/|title=Possibly more Sabah Covid-19 cases, but stay calm|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041320/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148679/possibly-more-sabah-covid-19-cases-but-stay-calm-/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 18 March, the total positive cases has risen to 103.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/18/21-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-bringing-total-to-103/|title=21 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, bringing total to 103|last=Santos|first=Jason|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319064601/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/18/21-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-bringing-total-to-103/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further seven infections were recorded on 20 March, raising the total infected to 119 with the first death caused by the virus was reported in Tawau involving a 58-year-old man who is one of the participant of the religious gathering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320124355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|title=Sabah's first Covid-19 case in Tawau dies|work=Daily Express|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320124355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/21/seven-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-119/|title=Seven new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 119|last=Lajiun|first=Jenne|work=Borneo Post|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065216/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/21/seven-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-119/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The religious gathering also causing the closure of [[palm oil]] plantations in three districts of Tawau, [[Lahad Datu District|Lahad Datu]] and [[Kinabatangan District|Kinabatangan]] in late March after several plantation workers who had participate in the gathering were found positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia-palmoil/malaysias-biggest-palm-oil-state-shuts-some-estates-after-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21B1BW|title=Malaysia's biggest palm oil state shuts some estates after virus outbreak|last1=Chu|first1=Mei Mei|last2=Sipalan|first2=Joseph|last3=Ananthalakshmi|first3=A.|last4=Elgood|first4=Giles|last5=Gopalakrishnan|first5=Raju|last6=Goodman|first6=David|agency=Reuters|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411072207/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia-palmoil/malaysias-biggest-palm-oil-state-shuts-some-estates-after-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21B1BW|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.antaranews.com/news/144638/10-indonesian-workers-in-malaysias-sabah-test-positive-for-covid-19|title=10 Indonesian workers in Malaysia's Sabah test positive for COVID-19|last1=Assegaf|first1=Fardah|last2=Rahmad Nasution|first2=Rusman|work=Antara|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415085407/https://en.antaranews.com/news/144638/10-indonesian-workers-in-malaysias-sabah-test-positive-for-covid-19|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, Sabah reported its first recovery of a coronavirus patient in [[Sandakan District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/27/sandakan-covid-19-patient-first-to-recover-in-sabah/|title=Sandakan Covid-19 patient first to recover in Sabah|last=Doksil|first=Mariah|work=Borneo Post|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413081148/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/27/sandakan-covid-19-patient-first-to-recover-in-sabah/|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The entire [[Gaya Island]] inhabitants in western coast of Sabah had also been put under close monitoring with 65.6% had been checked and 1,600 samples were taken.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/wilayah/2020/03/671219/covid-19-hampir-70-peratus-penduduk-pulau-gaya-disaring|title=COVID-19: Hampir 70 peratus penduduk Pulau Gaya disaring|trans-title=COVID-19: Nearly 70 percent of Gaya Island residents are screened|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Berita Harian|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415061232/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/wilayah/2020/03/671219/covid-19-hampir-70-peratus-penduduk-pulau-gaya-disaring|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 29 March, Tawau District have been declared as a red zone with the significant increase in positive cases which surpassing other districts within the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/30/tawau-declared-red-zone/|title=Tawau declared red zone|last=Sim Yee|first=Chok|work=Borneo Post|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418045240/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/30/tawau-declared-red-zone/|archive-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nUntil early April, a total of 7,173 coronavirus tests have been conducted by Sabah with the results of positive cases rising to 209.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-sabah-has-tested-7173-people-identified-209-positive-cases|title=Covid-19: Sabah has tested 7,173 people, identified 209 positive cases|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410024451/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-sabah-has-tested-7173-people-identified-209-positive-cases|archive-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same month, more than 90 people have recovered from the virus with three deaths have been reported since March;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150577/two-new-covid-19-cases-nine-more-recover-in-sabah/|title=Two new Covid-19 cases, nine more recover in Sabah|work=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411051618/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/06/second-death-in-sabah/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the latest involving a 66-year-old man in [[Tambunan District]] with a medical history of [[diabetes]], [[high blood pressure]] and [[kidney disease]] on 5 April along with a 62-year-old retired senior Sabah government official and tabligh worker with diabetic who died in [[Kota Kinabalu District]] on 10 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/06/second-death-in-sabah/|title=Second death in Sabah|last=Sim Yee|first=Chok|work=Borneo Post|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411051110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150577/two-new-covid-19-cases-nine-more-recover-in-sabah/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150525/retired-senior-sabah-govt-official-dies-of-covid-19/|title=Retired senior Sabah govt official dies of Covid-19|work=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416003246/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150525/retired-senior-sabah-govt-official-dies-of-covid-19/|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 April, a total of 231,980 people have been screened in the state out of which 16,654 samples have been taken for testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/11/covid-19-over-200000-people-screened-in-sabah-to-date|title=Covid-19: Over 200,000 people screened in Sabah to date|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412075044/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/11/covid-19-over-200000-people-screened-in-sabah-to-date|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The State Health Department has explained that further positive cases will only be known once 4,600 samples are cleared in the next two days by a special task force set up on 8 April, which previously ridden with backlog following the shortage of [[reagent]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150522/sabah-s-real-situation-to-be-known-soon-dept/|title=Sabah\u2019s real situation to be known soon: Dept|last1=Peter|first1=Anthea|last2=Into|first2=Ricardo|last3=Chok|first3=Christy|work=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411085647/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150522/sabah-s-real-situation-to-be-known-soon-dept/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Earlier on 6 April, a body of a 26-year-old man without identity documents was found hanged to a tree in a jungle area at Pondo Village in Gaya Island which are believed to be caused by suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/04/563288/mayat-tergantung-di-pokok|title=Mayat tergantung di pokok|trans-title=A corpse hanged to a tree|last=Riduan|first=Juwan|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416022057/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/04/563288/mayat-tergantung-di-pokok|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following a post-mortem confirmation of suicide on the deceased body and subsequent screening, it was also found out that the deceased body are positive with the coronavirus with the case is count as the fourth deaths in Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/13/sabah-suicide-victim-tests-positive|title=Sabah suicide victim tests positive|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=13 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414032208/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/13/sabah-suicide-victim-tests-positive|archive-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150818/sabah-has-four-covid-19-deaths/|title=Sabah has four Covid-19 deaths|work=Daily Express|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416002242/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150818/sabah-has-four-covid-19-deaths/|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Through a statement made by the Sabah Health Department on 13 April, a total of 5,007 tests have been done which is more than the expected of previously 4,600 backlog samples with a finding that a quarter of coronavirus cases in Kota Kinabalu are sporadic case.<ref name=\"one in four\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/14/one-in-four-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-are-sporadic-says-state-health-director|title=One in four Covid-19 cases in KK are sporadic, says state Health director|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415013040/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/14/one-in-four-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-are-sporadic-says-state-health-director|archive-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"sporadic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150817/25pc-of-kk-covid-19-cases-sporadic-harder-to-probe/|title=25pc of KK Covid-19 cases sporadic, harder to probe|work=Bernama|via=Daily Express|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416004016/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150817/25pc-of-kk-covid-19-cases-sporadic-harder-to-probe/|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 5,983 patients have been placed under home quarantine, with 956 in Tawau, 796 in Kota Kinabalu, 684 in Kunak, 624 in Papar, 603 in Penampang, 416 in Kinabatangan, 297 in Keningau and 231 in Sandakan while a further total of 853 people are placed in state-provided quarantine centres.<ref name=\"one in four\"/><ref name=\"sporadic\"/> Among the areas in [[Greater Kota Kinabalu]], [[Penampang District]] recorded the most sporadic cases numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/wilayah/2020/04/677391/jabatan-kesihatan-sabah-siasat-kes-sporadik-di-penampang|title=Jabatan Kesihatan Sabah siasat kes sporadik di Penampang|trans-title=The Sabah Health Department is investigating sporadic cases in Penampang|last=Miwil|first=Olivia|language=Malay|work=Berita Harian|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415064605/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/wilayah/2020/04/677391/jabatan-kesihatan-sabah-siasat-kes-sporadik-di-penampang|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFurther infection clusters were detected in both Sabah Women and Children's Hospital in [[Likas]] and Keningau Hospital from outside source which contracted by several of the hospital staff members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/18/new-covid-19-clusters-at-likas-keningau-hospitals-director/|title=New Covid-19 clusters at Likas, Keningau hospitals \u2013 director|last=Brian Joseph|first=Neil|work=Borneo Post|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418044538/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/18/new-covid-19-clusters-at-likas-keningau-hospitals-director/|archive-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another cluster was identified on 18 April at the Queen Elizabeth Hospital II.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/18/covid-19-queen-elizabeth-hospital-2-now-3rd-medical-facility-cluster-in-sabah/|title=Covid-19: Queen Elizabeth Hospital 2 now 3rd medical facility cluster in Sabah|last=Brian Joseph|first=Neil|work=Borneo Post|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421034818/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/18/covid-19-queen-elizabeth-hospital-2-now-3rd-medical-facility-cluster-in-sabah/|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 17 April, Kota Kinabalu District become the second red zone with the second most infections rate after Tawau District.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/17/kota-kinabalu-joins-tawau-as-second-red-zone-in-sabah/1857484|title=Kota Kinabalu joins Tawau as second red zone in Sabah|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=17 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418044527/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/17/kota-kinabalu-joins-tawau-as-second-red-zone-in-sabah/1857484|archive-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150923/kk-becomes-sabah-s-second-red-zone/|title=KK becomes Sabah\u2019s second Red Zone|work=Daily Express|date=17 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418044659/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150923/kk-becomes-sabah-s-second-red-zone/|archive-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was followed by Lahad Datu District the following day to become the third red zone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585653/lahad-datu-now-sabahs-third-covid-19-red-zone|title=Lahad Datu now Sabah's third Covid-19 red zone|last=Geraldine|first=Avila|work=New Straits Times|date=19 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421035058/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585653/lahad-datu-now-sabahs-third-covid-19-red-zone|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Through a survey of infections within the state, the virus are found to be infecting more males than females, with those infected aged between 1 and 80.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585835/covid-19-hits-more-boys-girls-sabah|title=Covid-19 hits more boys than girls in Sabah|last=Miwil|first=Olivia|work=New Straits Times|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421035702/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585835/covid-19-hits-more-boys-girls-sabah|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Implications ==\n=== Masks and hand sanitiser shortages ===\nSabah's capital city of [[Kota Kinabalu]] have reported shortages on both [[surgical masks]] and [[hand sanitiser]] since January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|title=Face masks, hand sanitiser sold out in JB, KK|agency=Bernama|via=The Malaysian Reserve|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223030553/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were reports that some businesses in the state taking advantage of the situation by selling overpriced masks during the period which led them being fined by the [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry]] branch of Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/07/three-businesses-in-sabah-selling-overpriced-masks-compounded-rm30500|title=Three businesses in Sabah selling overpriced masks compounded RM30,500|work=The Star|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318062534/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/07/three-businesses-in-sabah-selling-overpriced-masks-compounded-rm30500|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Panic buying ===\nMany of the state residents in each districts rush to stock up [[goods|essential items]] once the first positive case were reported among netizens even before the official announcement of the first case was made by the [[Government of Sabah|state government]] of Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|title=People starting to stock up goods in parts of Sabah after first Covid-19 case announced|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318060210/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-coronavirus-case-in-the-state|title=Panic-buying hits Sabah after first coronavirus case in the state|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=The Straits Times|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> With the rising number of positive cases been reported, residents in one of Sabah's district of [[Kunak District|Kunak]] are reportedly buying large quantities of rice to stock up foods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148947/panic-buying-continues/|title=Panic buying continues|last=Tabir|first=Ibrahim|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318060657/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148947/panic-buying-continues/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Deputy Chief Minister of Sabah [[Christina Liew]] has called on the community in her constituency of [[Tawau (federal constituency)|Tawau]] to avoid from panic buying despite the quick spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/covid-19-sabah-dcm-urges-tawau-community-to-avoid-panic-buying-essential-it/1845981|title=Covid-19: Sabah DCM urges Tawau community to avoid panic buying essential items|work=Bernama|via=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321062644/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/covid-19-sabah-dcm-urges-tawau-community-to-avoid-panic-buying-essential-it/1845981|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout the first week of the [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] (MCO), a supermarket in Papar also reportedly being stormed by shoppers who rush to buy [[sanitiser]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149297/papar-folks-storm-supermart-for-sanitisers/|title=Papar folks storm supermart for sanitisers|last1=Zabala|first1=Jeremy S|last2=Jikur|first2=Mardinah|last3=Rizan|first3=Eifa|last4=Tabir|first4=Ibrahim|work=Daily Express|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416005005/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149297/papar-folks-storm-supermart-for-sanitisers/|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Counter-measures by state government and other parties ==\nThe state government has released several guidelines to curb the spread of the virus and assured the public that essential goods will be sufficient despite the ongoing increase of infections and [[panic buying]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sabah-comes-up-with-steps-to-curb-spread-of-covid-19|title=Sabah comes up with steps to curb spread of Covid-19|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041616/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sabah-comes-up-with-steps-to-curb-spread-of-covid-19|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/sufficient-supply-of-essential-goods-in-sabah|title=Sufficient supply of essential goods in Sabah|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041138/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/sufficient-supply-of-essential-goods-in-sabah|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Food security ===\n{{Quote box\n| width  = 24%\n| align  = right\n| quote  = We have to look into [[food security]] \u2013 [[agriculture]], [[fisheries]], [[fruit]]s \u2013 all of that is needed. The [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|lockdown]] could be until May, June. Even if export is not encouraged, we will need adequate supply. People are losing their jobs, we cannot lose food supply as well. Next is to revive the economy. We will be looking into job opportunities. We are also forgoing tax collections in order to lighten the burden on people who are suffering.\n| source = \u2014Sabah Chief Minister [[Shafie Apdal]] on the Sabah plan to boost food production throughout the pandemic, 15 April 2020.<ref name=\"Sabah food security\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/584616/sabah-focus-sectors-ensure-food-security|title=Sabah to focus on sectors that ensure food security|last=Miwil|first=Olivia|work=New Straits Times|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416040807/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/584616/sabah-focus-sectors-ensure-food-security|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"boosting food production\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/15/sabah-cm-eyes-food-security-in-case-mco-extended/1857038|title=Sabah CM eyes food security in case MCO extended|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416041146/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/15/sabah-cm-eyes-food-security-in-case-mco-extended/1857038|archive-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nDue to the pandemic, the Sabah state government has been in the process to boost its [[food security]]. This were done with a total of 10,000 acres of land in Sapi Canal of Sandakan District and another 200 acres land in [[Long Pasia]] of [[Sipitang District]] and another in [[Membakut]] of [[Beaufort District]] being transformed into [[rice cultivation]] areas to cut the overdependence of rice supply from [[Rice production in Thailand|Thailand]] and [[Rice production in Vietnam|Vietnam]] since the available paddy field in [[Kota Belud District]] is not enough to supply the entire state.<ref name=\"Sabah food security\"/><ref name=\"boosting food production\"/>\n\nWith the oversupply of fruits and highland [[vegetable]]s in the state through the ongoing MCO, the Sabah state government also decided to export these excess supply to [[Brunei]] and markets around Malaysia which had been facing shortage of supplies and as a method to prevent the produce from going into waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/08/minister-fresh-greens-from-kundasang-on-their-way-to-main-markets-throughout-malaysia-brunei|title=Minister: Fresh greens from Kundasang on their way to main markets throughout Malaysia, Brunei|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421041124/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/08/minister-fresh-greens-from-kundasang-on-their-way-to-main-markets-throughout-malaysia-brunei|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/20/covid-19-sabah-to-export-vegetables-to-neighbouring-brunei-to-address-glut/1858431|title=Covid-19: Sabah to export vegetables to neighbouring Brunei to address glut|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421041309/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/20/covid-19-sabah-to-export-vegetables-to-neighbouring-brunei-to-address-glut/1858431|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Prevention for immigrations ===\n[[File:Temporary Prohibition in Sabah due to the Coronavirus outbreak, 2020.jpg|thumb|left|Prohibition dated 7 February 2020 issued by the [[Government of Sabah]].]]\nSince the earlier several suspected cases in Sabah's capital of Kota Kinabalu, all direct flights between the state with [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|mainland China]] have been stopped indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|title=Wuhan coronavirus: All flights from China to Sabah suspended as state govt imposes travel ban|work=Borneo Post|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201050803/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]] were imposed by the state government towards the three most affected countries by the virus; comprising [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] by March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|title=Sabah bans travellers from Iran and Italy|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=10 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314064405/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|title=Sabah extends Covid-19 travel restrictions to S Korea|work=Daily Express|date=29 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314062724/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn line with the announcement of the MCO made by the [[Government of Malaysia|federal government]] of Malaysia since the growing number of infections within the country, non-Sabahans are barred from entering the state with immediate effect as additional efforts to counter the increase in the number of positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148950/non-sabahans-barred/|title=Non-Sabahans barred|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318061532/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148950/non-sabahans-barred/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sabahan university students in Peninsular Malaysia with settlement problem during the order period may stay at Sabah House, Cheras with food provided by the state government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-mahasiswa-sabah-di-semenanjung-boleh-tinggal-di-rumah-sabah-cheras-234220|title=COVID-19: Mahasiswa Sabah di Semenanjung boleh tinggal di Rumah Sabah Cheras|last=Zulkepli|first=Ruzaini|work=Astro Awani|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322084051/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-mahasiswa-sabah-di-semenanjung-boleh-tinggal-di-rumah-sabah-cheras-234220|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Malay|trans-title=COVID-19: Sabah University Students in Peninsular may stay at Sabah House Cheras}}</ref> Civil servants across the country are exempts from the ban despite each of them still must showing valid confirmation letters that are issued by their heads of departments for each specific task.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37647|title=State govt allows exemption for civil servants|last=Ebit|first=Jason Jack|work=New Sabah Times|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321064249/http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37647|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the reports that there is another Muslim religious gathering to be held at [[Gowa]], [[South Sulawesi]] in neighbouring [[Indonesia]], the Sabah state government implements immediate action to ban the entry of those who attended the gathering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149153/sabah-bans-indonesia-tabligh-attendees/|title=Sabah bans Indonesia Tabligh attendees|work=New Straits Times|via=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065827/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149153/sabah-bans-indonesia-tabligh-attendees/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Movement control order and bans on mass gathering events ===\nAnnual cultural events in Sabah such as the [[Kaamatan]] ([[Kadazan-Dusun|Kadazan-Dusun festival]]) and Kalimaran ([[Murut people|Murut festival]]) have been cancelled,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|title=Kaamatan Festival 2020 cancelled due to Covid-19|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314021932/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|title=Dua pesta tahunan Sabah dibatalkan|trans-title=Two annual Sabah festivals are cancelled|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315044826/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Catholic Masses]] and [[Good Friday]] in the state were observed through a [[live broadcast]] online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|title=Suspension of Catholic Masses and gatherings|work=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320040624/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574582/masses-sabah-go-online|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574582/masses-sabah-go-online|title=Masses in Sabah go online|last=Geraldine|first=Avila|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023506/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-and-sarawak-to-observe-good-friday-online|title=Sabah and Sarawak to observe Good Friday online|last1=Then|first1=Stephen|last2=Lee|first2=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411063811/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-and-sarawak-to-observe-good-friday-online|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Muslim [[Friday sermon]]s and every [[salah al jama'ah|congregational prayer]]s had been postponed since March as announced by the Sabah Fatwa Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://republika.co.id/berita/q8r99z430/sabah-perpanjang-penangguhan-kegiatan-di-masjid|title=Sabah Perpanjang Penangguhan Kegiatan di Masjid|trans-title=Sabah Extends the Suspension of Activities at the Mosque|last1=Hafil|first1=Muhammad|last2=Oktaviani|first2=Zahratul|language=Indonesian|work=Republika.co.id|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414035312/https://republika.co.id/berita/q8r99z430/sabah-perpanjang-penangguhan-kegiatan-di-masjid|archive-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> International sporting events such as the [[Borneo International Marathon]] scheduled to be held in Sabah also have been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/09/borneo-international-marathon-cancelled-refunds-underway/1855016|title=Borneo International Marathon cancelled, refunds underway|last=Tee|first=Kenneth|work=The Malay Mail|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412015250/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/09/borneo-international-marathon-cancelled-refunds-underway/1855016|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing reports of poor compliance to the MCO in the state capital of Kota Kinabalu, the [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (PDRM) has imposed citywide round-the-clock roadblocks aimed at warning obstinate individuals who go against the order until the end of the two week period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/18/poor-compliance-to-movement-control-order-in-sabah|title=Poor compliance to movement control order in Sabah|last1=Vanar|first1=Muguntan|last2=Lee|first2=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063147/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/18/poor-compliance-to-movement-control-order-in-sabah|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37652|title=Round-the-clock roadblocks by police in Kota Kinabalu|last=Nicholas|first=Jonathan|work=New Sabah Times|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063323/http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37652|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With the increasing enforcement being conducted, city folks are getting better at complying the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|title=MCO compliance improving in Kota Kinabalu|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063551/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government also sealed off coronavirus hotspots in major towns such as in several areas in Kota Kinabalu, [[Sandakan]] and Tawau to minimise movement amid a growing number of cases in these areas including ordering some factories and plantations in [[Kalabakan]] and Lahad Datu with detection of cases to cease their operation as well as stopping [[barter|barter trading]] between east coast of Sabah and the neighbouring [[Philippines]] and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/sabah-covid-19-039hotspots039-sealed-off-to-reduce-movement-exposure|title=Sabah Covid-19 'hotspots' sealed off to reduce movement, exposure|work=The Star|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411062733/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/sabah-covid-19-039hotspots039-sealed-off-to-reduce-movement-exposure|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the second extension of the MCO announced on 10 April, the Sabah government has give relaxation to palm oil plantations and mills in six eastern Sabah districts of Kalabakan, Kinabatangan, [[Kunak District|Kunak]], Lahad Datu, [[Semporna District|Semporna]] and Tawau to operate under certain conditions that need to be complied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150579/oil-palm-estates-can-operate-on-conditions-cm/|title=Oil palm estates can operate on conditions: CM|last=Dzulkifli|first=Hayati|work=Daily Express|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411121304/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150579/oil-palm-estates-can-operate-on-conditions-cm/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Quarantine and treatment centres ===\nOn 19 March, Sabah Assistant Minister of the local government and the Ministry of Housing Hiew Vun Zin said that there are a total of nine buildings in the People's Housing Program (PPR) Batu Putih in [[Sandakan District]], three of which are blocks H, I and G will be serving as isolation centres.<ref name=\"Sabah PPR quarantine centre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2237106.html|title=\u5168\u56fd\u9996\u95f4\u00b7\u4eba\u6c11\u7ec4\u5c4b\u5145\u9694\u79bb\u4e2d\u5fc3|trans-title=The first PPR Isolation Centre in Sabah|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"self-quarantine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/30-self-quarantine-at-sandakan-ppr/|title=30 self-quarantine at Sandakan PPR|work=Borneo Post|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320024309/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/30-self-quarantine-at-sandakan-ppr/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Each building has 100 units and each unit has 3 bedrooms. As long as they are tested as [[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]] by the Health Bureau and [[Duchess of Kent Hospital]], the authorities will send them and their families to the isolation centre for 14 days of isolation. At the time there is more than 30 people were being quarantined at the centre, including six families.<ref name=\"Sabah PPR quarantine centre\"/><ref name=\"self-quarantine\"/> The State Health Department has put a total of 350 beds on standby for coronavirus infected patient.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149152/350-beds-on-standby-for-sabah-cases-dept/|title=350 beds on standby for Sabah cases: Dept|last=Ralon|first=Larry|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065604/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149152/350-beds-on-standby-for-sabah-cases-dept/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA total of RM2 million had been set by the Sabah government for the transformation of Likas Sports Complex into makeshift coronavirus medical facility as a branch of the Queen Elizabeth Hospital from a RM200 million fund allocated for infrastructure development in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585880/sabah-turn-likas-sports-complex-makeshift-covid-19-medical-facility|title=Sabah to turn Likas Sports Complex into makeshift Covid-19 medical facility|last=Miwil|first=Olivia|work=New Straits Times|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421064841/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/585880/sabah-turn-likas-sports-complex-makeshift-covid-19-medical-facility|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This includes the upgrading of 39 premises that have been gazetted as quarantine centres for coronavirus and another 13 buildings in the midst of identifying as of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/21/39-quarantine-centres-to-be-upgraded/|title=39 quarantine centres to be upgraded|last=Lai|first=Nancy|work=Borneo Post|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421065045/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/21/39-quarantine-centres-to-be-upgraded/|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Shortage of coronavirus test kits reagents ====\nFollowing reports of the shortage of [[COVID-19 testing|coronavirus test kits]] reagents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/test-kit-shortage-hampers-sabahs-anti-virus-efforts/|title=Test kit shortage hampers Sabah\u2019s anti-virus efforts|last=Santos|first=Jason|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411052528/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/test-kit-shortage-hampers-sabahs-anti-virus-efforts/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the Sabah government has acquired an immediate supply of 5,000 reagents from [[Singapore]] on 3 April through a joint efforts between the state government and [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGOs) with another 5,000 arrived the following day.<ref name=\"test kits supply\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150135/sabah-decides-not-to-wait/|title=Sabah decides not to wait|work=Daily Express|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411052635/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150135/sabah-decides-not-to-wait/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"test kits with medical supplies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/sabah-gets-much-needed-covid-19-test-kits-medical-supplies-flown-in|title=Sabah gets much-needed Covid-19 test kits, medical supplies flown in|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411054023/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/sabah-gets-much-needed-covid-19-test-kits-medical-supplies-flown-in|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The reagents along with critically low medical supplies donated by the federal government specifically for medical frontliners in Sabah were flown through a [[Royal Malaysian Air Force]] (RMAF) flight.<ref name=\"test kits supply\"/><ref name=\"test kits with medical supplies\"/>\n\n== Aid to Sabah on the pandemic ==\n=== Local aid ===\nThe Sabah state government has announced a total of RM670 million aid to help ease the burden of the people affected by the outbreak with 15 measures had been formulated under the package, involving three categories including assistance to frontliners staffs and the affected people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/business/news.php?id=1824877|title=Sabah announces RM670 million COVID-19 aid package|agency=Bernama|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The federal government had donated a total of 200,000 face masks, 50,000 gloves, 10,000 litres of sanitisers and a variety of medical equipments for frontliners in Sabah.<ref name=\"test kits with medical supplies\"/> On 10 April, a further 3 million [[surgical mask]]s meant for the distribution to every home in Sabah were delivered by the federal government through another RMAF flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-receives-three-million-face-masks-from-federal-govt|title=Sabah receives three million face masks from Federal Govt|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412072241/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-receives-three-million-face-masks-from-federal-govt|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Basic essential items aid also being extended by NGOs to families of [[illegal immigrants in Malaysia|illegal immigrants]] in the state following reports that they have been abandoned by irresponsible employer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150617/abandoned-illegals-get-aid/|title=Abandoned illegals get aid|work=Free Malaysia Today|via=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413102819/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150617/abandoned-illegals-get-aid/|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral local individuals who requested anonymity has donated a total of 10,000 pieces of 3-ply surgical masks to hospitals around Sabah.<ref name=\"masks from donors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.borneotoday.net/covid-19-sabah-healthcare-workers-receive-25400-masks-from-donors/|title=Covid-19: Sabah Healthcare Workers Receive 25,400 Masks From Donors|last=Andrew|first=Ilona|work=Borneo Today|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=22 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422063949/https://www.borneotoday.net/covid-19-sabah-healthcare-workers-receive-25400-masks-from-donors/|archive-date=22 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Through the \"Star Frontliners Initiative\", a total of 150,000 [[surgical glove]]s were delivered to the frontliners in Sabah's Queen Elizabeth Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/21/a-gift-of-300000-gloves-for-frontliners|title=A gift of 300,000 gloves for frontliners|last1=Ling|first1=Sharon|last2=Lee|first2=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421064726/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/21/a-gift-of-300000-gloves-for-frontliners|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Until April, the state government has received contributions worth RM11,380,000 in cash and other different kinds of donations from various state statutory bodies, NGOs and private sectors of the state in support of its efforts to stem the virus spread within Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/21/over-rm11-mln-worth-of-contributions-to-combat-covid-19/|title=Over RM11 mln worth of contributions to combat Covid-19|work=Borneo Post|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421065650/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/21/over-rm11-mln-worth-of-contributions-to-combat-covid-19/|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign aid ===\n[[China]]'s Consulate-General in Kota Kinabalu has announced that medical aid to be dispatched to Sabah to aid their struggle against the virus and reciprocate the people's of Sabah recent assistance to [[Mainland China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|title=EXCLUSIVE: China to send medical aid to Sabah|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321070223/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|title=China to reciprocate Sabah's kindness \u2013 Liang|work=Borneo Post|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324032130/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first aid came to Sabah on 29 March, which consists of 83 boxes of face masks with 2,000 pieces before a further 170,000 boxes of face masks, personal equipments and sanitisers delivered directly to the Sabah state government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/03/670760/sabah-terima-170000-kotak-topeng-muka-ppe-dari-china|title=Sabah terima 170,000 kotak topeng muka, PPE dari China|trans-title=Sabah received 170,000 boxes of face masks, PPE from China|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Berita Harian|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406015201/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/03/670760/sabah-terima-170000-kotak-topeng-muka-ppe-dari-china|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|title=Sabah gets fresh boost of medical masks, supplies from China|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405151732/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|title=China sends masks and sanitisers|last=Ralon|first=Larry|work=Daily Express|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405160213/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another 20,000 surgical masks destined for Sabah's healthcare frontliner workers were delivered in early April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/region/news.php?id=1828245|title=Sabah receives additional 20,000 surgical masks from China|agency=Bernama|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Through the efforts and initiatives of the Sabah Ma-Zhong Friendship Association, a total of RM100,000 worth of medical aid and masks were delivered to Sabah frontliners comprising 10,000 pieces of 3-ply surgical masks from the Sichuan Federation of Returned Overseas Chinese, Sichuan Overseas Chinese Business Association, and Sichuan Tiandan Trading Co. Ltd., 5,000 pieces of [[N95 face mask]]s from the Fujian Provincial People's Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries and another 400 pieces of KN95 face masks from the Shanxi Provincial Federation of Returned Overseas Chinese and Shanxi Overseas Exchanges Association.<ref name=\"masks from donors\"/> Chinese medical experts specialised in respirology, intensive care, psychiatry, infectious diseases, data analysis, virology and [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM) also being dispatched to Sabah to share their expertise in dealing with the virus with some of the expertise has experience throughout the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Hubei|coronavirus pandemic in Hubei Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/19/chinese-medical-experts-to-visit-sarawak-sabah-to-share-expertise-in-fight-against-covid-19/|title=Chinese medical experts to visit Sarawak, Sabah to share expertise in fight against Covid-19|last=Pim|first=Lim How|work=Borneo Post|date=19 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421070711/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/19/chinese-medical-experts-to-visit-sarawak-sabah-to-share-expertise-in-fight-against-covid-19/|archive-date=21 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Filipinos in Malaysia|Filipino]] residents in Sabah are being channelled monetary aid by the [[Government of the Philippines|Filipino government]] through the \"DOLE-AKAP Cash Assistance\" while\n[[Indonesians in Malaysia|Indonesian]] residents in the state were also given aid through their [[Government of Indonesia|government]] consulate-general office in the form of essential items aid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150713/filipinos-in-sabah-entitled-to-aid-by-their-govt/|title=Filipinos in Sabah entitled to aid by their govt|last=Fabian|first=Nikko|work=Daily Express|date=13 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415083252/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150713/filipinos-in-sabah-entitled-to-aid-by-their-govt/|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kaltara.prokal.co/read/news/32779-wni-di-sabah-terdampak-lockdown-diberi-kebutuhan-pangan|title=WNI di Sabah Terdampak Lockdown Diberi Kebutuhan Pangan|trans-title=Indonesian Citizens in Sabah Affected by Lockdown Given Food Needs|language=Indonesian|work=Radar Tarakan|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415083808/https://kaltara.prokal.co/read/news/32779-wni-di-sabah-terdampak-lockdown-diberi-kebutuhan-pangan|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Malaysia|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://jknsabah.moh.gov.my/V8/index.php/en/ Sabah State Health Department website] \u2013 Further details on the coronavirus outbreak in Sabah\n* [http://sabahoutbreak.com/ Covid-19 Cases in Sabah on Sabah Outbreak] \u2013 Current updates on the coronavirus outbreak in Sabah\n* [https://www.sabahalert.com/ Covid-19 Cases in Sabah on Sabah Alerts] \u2013 SabahAlerts Covid-19 online tracker\n\n{{History of East Malaysia}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sabah]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia by state|Sabah]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Sabah, Malaysia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Sabah\n| width           =\n| image           =\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   =\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| map1            =\n| legend1         =\n| map2            =\n| legend2         =\n| map3            =\n| legend3         =\n| map4            =\n| legend4         =\n| map5            =\n| legend5         =\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Sabah]], Malaysia\n| first_case      =\n| arrival_date    = 12 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, month